// nil_ordered_cmp_reversed_reject (F2 follow-up): the REVERSED-operand
// direction `nil < p` — commit 199f94b's own message notes `p < nil` was
// already safe by the fallback's asymmetry, and identifies `nil < p` as the
// actual new-code risk: type_compatible's nil-assignability arm (types.c)
// could in principle let this slip through the generic comparison fallback
// if the ordered-comparison guard (expression_helpers.c) ever regressed.
// Go: "invalid operation: nil < p (operator < not defined on untyped nil)".
// This fixture is the regression pin nil_ordered_cmp_reject.goo (forward
// direction only) was missing.
package main

func main() {
	var p *int
	_ = nil < p
}
